<article>
    <h1>An&#xAD;jali Ragu&#xAD;ra&#xAD;man rec&#xAD;om&#xAD;mends</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200724/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-24"><time>2020-07-24</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | HAPPENINGS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>A self-ti­tled al­bum typ­i­cally marks a change in a mu­si­cian’s di­rec­tion, a tran­si­tion point or, more of­ten, the clear­est dis­til­la­tion of his or her work.</p>
    <p>It took Lon­doner Lianne La Havas (right) three al­bums to reach her</p>
    <p>“this is me” mo­ment, crys­tallised in open­ing track Bit­ter­sweet, where she sings “bit­ter­sweet sum­mer rain/I’m born again/all my bro­ken pieces”.</p>
    <p>The record – which deals with change, loss and grow­ing up – comes in the af­ter­math of a five-year pe­riod of tur­moil that in­cluded a ma­jor break-up and the deaths of her grand­mother, great-grand­mother and mu­sic men­tor Prince.</p>
    <p>She has since learnt to smile through the tears, wipe them away and stand a lit­tle taller – just as how she dis­plays courage on the track of the same name.</p>
    <p>Her self-as­sured­ness seeps through on the stripped-back slow jam Green Pa­paya (“Take me home/let’s make real love, real love”) and the in­tro­spec­tive Sour Flower.</p>
    <p>“No more look­ing out for some­one else/but me,” she vows in the ar­rest­ing seven-minute num­ber, where del­i­cate gui­tar pick­ing evolves into a jazz drum solo fea­tur­ing hand claps.</p>
    <p>The al­bum is the work of a con­fi­dent and free woman who has found her cen­tre again.</p>

